  <content>
    <title>BA Knowledge Areas Detail</title>

    <summary>Detailed reference for all six BABOK Knowledge Areas (KA-1 through KA-6): per-KA task table, key outputs, linked methodologies, and the canonical workflow sequence for greenfield engagements and change requests. This is a routing and reference index — it does not replace per-methodology folders. Use it to select KAs, sequence subagents, and audit artifact coverage.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>BABOK knowledge areas overlap and can be applied in multiple sequences. Without a concrete task-level reference, agents default to KA-5 (modeling) on any input, missing stakeholder mapping (KA-1), strategy alignment (KA-4), and traceability maintenance (KA-3). This detail file provides the KA dispatch table and typical sequencing that prevents those defaults.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new BA engagement: scope which KAs apply and in what order.</item>
        <item>Routing a vague stakeholder request to the correct KA and downstream methodology.</item>
        <item>Building a multi-step agentic pipeline crossing several KAs (elicit → model → validate → trace).</item>
        <item>Auditing an existing BA artifact set for KA coverage gaps before a release gate.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>You already know the methodology — go straight to that methodology's folder.</item>
        <item>Pure product discovery with no formal requirements artifacts — use product-manager continuous-discovery instead.</item>
        <item>Pure UX research — use pro/ux/ux-researcher/ skills instead.</item>
        <item>One-off ad-hoc questions that produce no tracked artifact.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="knowledge-areas">
      <p>Purpose: define approach, identify stakeholders, plan governance.</p>

      <section name="ka-1-planning-and-monitoring">
        <p>KA-1: Business Analysis Planning and Monitoring</p>
        <p>Purpose: define approach, identify stakeholders, plan governance.</p>
        <list>
          <item>Plan BA Approach — how BA will be performed → BA approach document.</item>
          <item>Plan Stakeholder Engagement — identify and plan work with stakeholders → stakeholder engagement approach.</item>
          <item>Plan Governance — decision-making for requirements → governance approach.</item>
          <item>Plan Information Management — how BA info is stored and accessed → information management approach.</item>
          <item>Identify Improvements — assess BA performance → BA performance improvements.</item>
        </list>
        <p>Methodologies: ba-planning, stakeholder-analysis. Outputs: BA approach document, stakeholder register, governance framework, communication plan.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="ka-2-elicitation-and-collaboration">
        <p>KA-2: Elicitation and Collaboration</p>
        <p>Purpose: obtain information from stakeholders and confirm results.</p>
        <list>
          <item>Prepare for Elicitation — scope, technique selection → elicitation activity plan.</item>
          <item>Conduct Elicitation — draw out relevant information → elicitation results (unconfirmed).</item>
          <item>Confirm Results — verify understanding → elicitation results (confirmed).</item>
          <item>Communicate BA Information — shared understanding → BA communication.</item>
          <item>Manage Collaboration — encourage stakeholder cooperation → updated stakeholder engagement.</item>
        </list>
        <p>Methodologies: elicitation-techniques. Techniques: interviews, workshops, document analysis, observation, surveys, prototyping, brainstorming, focus groups.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="ka-3-requirements-lifecycle-management">
        <p>KA-3: Requirements Lifecycle Management</p>
        <p>Purpose: manage and maintain requirements throughout the solution lifecycle.</p>
        <list>
          <item>Trace Requirements — alignment at different levels → requirements (traced).</item>
          <item>Maintain Requirements — accurate and consistent → requirements (maintained).</item>
          <item>Prioritize Requirements — rank by importance → requirements (prioritized).</item>
          <item>Assess Changes — evaluate proposed changes → change assessment.</item>
          <item>Approve Requirements — agreement and approval → requirements (approved).</item>
        </list>
        <p>Methodologies: requirements-traceability, requirements-lifecycle, requirements-prioritization. Outputs: traceability matrix, requirements baseline, prioritized backlog, change impact analysis.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="ka-4-strategy-analysis">
        <p>KA-4: Strategy Analysis</p>
        <p>Purpose: define the future state needed to address business needs.</p>
        <list>
          <item>Analyze Current State — understand existing environment → current state description.</item>
          <item>Define Future State — define goals and objectives → future state description.</item>
          <item>Assess Risks — identify uncertainties → risk assessment results.</item>
          <item>Define Change Strategy — approach to achieve future state → change strategy.</item>
        </list>
        <p>Methodologies: strategy-analysis. Techniques: gap analysis, SWOT, business model canvas, capability assessment, risk analysis.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="ka-5-requirements-analysis-and-design-definition">
        <p>KA-5: Requirements Analysis and Design Definition</p>
        <p>Purpose: structure, specify, model, verify, validate requirements, and define design options.</p>
        <list>
          <item>Specify and Model Requirements — → requirements (specified/modeled).</item>
          <item>Verify Requirements — quality standards met → requirements (verified).</item>
          <item>Validate Requirements — alignment with business goals → requirements (validated).</item>
          <item>Define Requirements Architecture — requirements support each other → requirements architecture.</item>
          <item>Define Design Options — solution approaches → design options.</item>
          <item>Analyze Value and Recommend — assess options → solution recommendation.</item>
        </list>
        <p>Methodologies: use-case-modeling, user-story-mapping, data-analysis, business-process-analysis, decision-analysis, interface-analysis, requirements-validation, acceptance-criteria, requirements-documentation. Techniques: use cases, user stories, process modeling (BPMN), data modeling (ERD), decision tables, interface specifications, prototyping.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="ka-6-solution-evaluation">
        <p>KA-6: Solution Evaluation</p>
        <p>Purpose: assess solution performance and value delivered.</p>
        <list>
          <item>Measure Performance — define measurement → solution performance measures.</item>
          <item>Analyze Measures — examine data → performance analysis.</item>
          <item>Assess Solution Limitations — investigate problems → solution limitations.</item>
          <item>Assess Enterprise Limitations — enterprise factor impacts → enterprise limitations.</item>
          <item>Recommend Actions — identify value improvements → value improvement recommendations.</item>
        </list>
        <p>Methodologies: solution-assessment. Outputs: performance metrics, value realization report, improvement recommendations, lessons learned.</p>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="workflow">
      <p>Knowledge Area Relationships</p>
      <p>The six KAs are not sequential — they interact throughout the project lifecycle:</p>
      <list>
        <item>KA-1 (Planning) defines the approach that governs how all other KAs operate.</item>
        <item>KA-2 (Elicitation) and KA-5 (Analysis) feed each other iteratively: elicitation produces raw material, analysis structures and validates it, gaps trigger more elicitation.</item>
        <item>KA-3 (Lifecycle) operates continuously — tracing, maintaining, and approving requirements as they evolve through all other KAs.</item>
        <item>KA-4 (Strategy) provides the current and future state context that KA-2 and KA-5 must operate within.</item>
        <item>KA-6 (Evaluation) assesses the built solution and feeds learnings back into KA-1 and KA-3 for the next cycle.</item>
      </list>

      <section name="typical-ba-workflow-greenfield">
        <p>Typical BA Workflow — Greenfield</p>
        <rule>
          <statement>For a greenfield engagement, sequence KAs as: KA-1 → KA-4 → KA-2 → KA-5 (model) → KA-3 (prioritize and approve) → KA-5 (design) → build → KA-6.</statement>
          <rationale>Starting without KA-1 produces unplanned elicitation; starting without KA-4 produces requirements disconnected from business strategy. KA-3 between modeling and design ensures only approved requirements enter the design phase.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>KA-1: Plan BA approach, identify stakeholders.</item>
          <item>KA-4: Analyze current state, define future state.</item>
          <item>KA-2: Elicit requirements from stakeholders.</item>
          <item>KA-5: Analyze, model, and validate requirements.</item>
          <item>KA-3: Trace, prioritize, and approve requirements.</item>
          <item>KA-5: Define design options, recommend solution.</item>
          <item>Build: solution implemented.</item>
          <item>KA-6: Evaluate solution, recommend improvements.</item>
          <item>KA-3: Update requirements based on learnings.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="typical-ba-workflow-change-request">
        <p>Typical BA Workflow — Change Request</p>
        <rule>
          <statement>For a change request, jump directly to KA-3 (assess the change) and KA-5 (analyze impact on existing requirements). Skip KA-1 and KA-4 unless the change redefines the project scope or strategic goals.</statement>
          <rationale>Repeating full KA sequencing for a scope change wastes time; the existing BA plan and strategy analysis remain valid unless the change is transformational.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="underlying-competencies">
        <p>Underlying Competencies — All KAs</p>
        <p>Competencies required across all six knowledge areas:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Analytical — creative thinking, decision making, systems thinking, problem solving.</item>
          <item>Behavioral — ethics, accountability, trustworthiness, adaptability.</item>
          <item>Business — business acumen, industry knowledge, organization knowledge.</item>
          <item>Communication — verbal, written, listening, non-verbal.</item>
          <item>Interaction — facilitation, leadership, teamwork, negotiation.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="routing-rules">
        <p>Routing Rules</p>
        <rule>
          <statement>Classify every BA request into one or more KAs before generating any deliverable. Use the KA routing result as shared state that all downstream agents read — never re-classify per task.</statement>
          <rationale>Skipping the routing step causes agents to draft KA-5 specs when the actual gap is KA-1 stakeholder mapping; re-classifying per task produces inconsistent results across the pipeline.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <antipattern>
          <description>LLMs default to KA-5 (modelling) on any input.</description>
          <reason>Most real project failures are in KA-1 (no stakeholder map) or KA-3 (no traceability). Make the planner explicitly score all 6 KAs before dispatching.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>

    <see-also>
      <ref slug="knowledge-areas-overview"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
